Raw dev notes -- Taming the Watchdog: Alert Fatigue Edition

Okay, so the "Personal Information Hub" project. This is basically my self-hosted brain, a little server instance that pulls together various bits of personal data, dashboards, and services I rely on daily. Think personal analytics, home automation hooks, and a few custom APIs. It's critical for me, so keeping it up and running is a big deal. That's where the "watchdog" comes in – a system designed to monitor its health and alert me if something goes sideways.

This past week was all about refining that watchdog. Initially, I had a pretty aggressive setup. If the main service went down, the watchdog would trigger an "L3 reboot" – basically, a hard reset of the underlying system. The idea was to be super proactive, but it turned out to be overkill. The first big change was replacing that L3 reboot with just a Pushover notification. I realized that a hard reboot was often more disruptive than helpful, especially if it was a transient issue. Sometimes, I just need to *know* it's down, not have it violently restarted.

Then, I noticed I was still getting spammed. Even with just notifications, the L3 events were triggering multiple Pushover alerts. So, I went in and dropped the L3 Pushover entirely, opting for a "once-per-outage" alerting strategy. The goal here was to cut down on alert fatigue. There's nothing worse than your phone buzzing constantly when you're trying to diagnose an issue, or worse, when you're just trying to relax. If it's down, I need one clear alert, not a cascade of them.

The final piece of the puzzle was dealing with planned downtime. I had a planned restart of the main server coming up, and I knew from past experience that the watchdog would dutifully send me "STOPPED" notifications, even though I *knew* it was going to stop. So, I added a fix to suppress those duplicate STOPPED Pushover alerts during planned restarts. It's a small thing, but it makes a huge difference in keeping the alert channel clean and trustworthy.

Honestly, this whole experience has been a bit of a wake-up call about alert management. My initial thought was "more alerts = more informed," but it's actually the opposite. Too many alerts, especially redundant or expected ones, just make you tune them out. It's like the boy who cried wolf. I was becoming desensitized to the notifications, which defeats the entire purpose of having a watchdog. It felt a bit frustrating at times, realizing my "fix" was actually creating more noise, but it was a good lesson in operational maturity. Even for a personal project, thinking about the human element – my own sanity – is crucial. It's not just about the code working, but about the system being *livable*.

Next up: More granular health checks for specific services within the hub.
